external_knowledge:
- "regular guests" refers to customers who have made bookings within the last 30 days;
- "stayed the most" is determined by the total number of bookings per customer;
- "spent the most" is based on the total cost of their bookings;
- "top five" indicates limiting the results to the first five customers with the highest booking and spending activity.

- "Unique voyagers" refers to distinct customers;
- "Set sail on a new journey" metaphorically represents making a new booking;
- "Within the last week" corresponds to the date range from today back seven days.

sql:
SELECT DISTINCT customer_id
FROM bookings
WHERE booking_date >= date('now', '-7 days');

SELECT hotels.hotel_name, chains.chain_name
FROM hotels
INNER JOIN chains ON hotels.chain_id = chains.chain_id;

external_knowledge:
- "last year of the 2020s" refers to the year 2022;
- "cost of their stay" is equivalent to the total cost of the booking;
- "excluding those who cancelled their reservations" means only include bookings that were not cancelled.

sql:
SELECT DISTINCT customer_name
FROM customers
WHERE loyalty_program_enrolled = 1;

external_knowledge:
- "reservations" refers to bookings made by customers;
- "count of their bookings" refers to the number of reservations a customer has made in a particular city;
- "highest spenders" refers to customers with the largest total costs of bookings.

sql:
SELECT c.customer_name, b.total_cost
FROM customers c
JOIN bookings b ON c.customer_id = b.customer_id;

